description.text:
This can be used to connect sections of PVC pipe together. Cut the PVC to length and place one of these connectors in each section. Use a bolt to hold them together. The teeth allow you to adjust the angle. There is a 12 tooth and a 30 tooth version. As created it should fit PVC with an inner diameter of 0.5", it has a 1 degree draft.

10/15/2017 Added a tetrahedral part, could be used for molecular modeling if scaled down for small tubing.

10/7/2017 Added a 12 tooth version with right and left parts so it can go together to make a 90 degree or 180 degree angle. This is more useful on smaller parts which have trouble with the teeth meshing together.

10/2/2017 Added 24 (15 degree) parts which are capable of 75 degree, 90 degree, 105 degree angles, etc.

Added another section which should center on the middle of the pipe instead of being offset.
Modified SLC30MID because when I printed it the parts would not fit together due to limited resolution of the printer I was using.

Added another part at with the toothed circle at right angles.

Added a couple smaller volume connectors for use with a number 6 screw and nut. Modified the number 6 parts for greater angle and better fit.

Added an outside connector for the pipe I am using.

Added SLC4Way so that I can actually make the spider.

Added a perpendicular connector.

9/27/2017 Added 6 way, 5 way, 4 way, and 3 way right angle connectors.

These connectors are all designed for work with a .5" ID tube but you may need to scale it depending on the tubing:

1/2" SCPI pipe (available at Menards) works without scaling (measures .4935" ID)
1/2" PVC pipe measures .622" ID so you need to scale by 126%
3/4" PVC pipe measures .822" ID so you need to scale by 166%

Added a piece for connecting 1/4" doweling

9/28/2017 Added a corner for creating an icosahedral design. You would need 12 of these for an icosahedron.

From the edge of Eternia I present to you the Gray-Skull Dice Tower!

The Lid and Core are designed in a way to turn the core of the dice tower within the outer tower allowing you to store your dice inside the Greyskull Tower. The Lid keeps it all safe inside.

description.text:
M3 nut holder for Solidoodle M3 Z-axis rod hack. See http://www.soliforum.com/post/127928/#p127928 for more background on the mod. It didn't appear that anyone had yet posted a Thing for the 3mm nut hugger so I cooked this up based on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:159671 (amazing thank you!). I projected the geometry and adapted for smaller m3 nut vs 5/16". I only printed the one part. My tolerances were a little tight so I heated an m3 nut with a lighter and pressed it in. I insert two nuts into the hex with hammer or lighter and then cap on either side with a retainer part.

BoM:

  • 18-8 Stainless Steel Fully Threaded Rod, Meets DIN 975, M3-0.5 Thread Size, 1 m Length, Right Hand Threads for $12 (have plenty of rod leftover for next project!
  • 3mmx5mm 16mm Dia 20mm Length Motor Shaft Beam Coupler Coupling Connect for $6.84
  • 2 x M3 nut to insert into hugger
  • small amount of super glue... perhaps ABS slurry would work
  • 4 x screw and nut to mount ... I used 6-32 screws since I'm drowning in non-metric hardware ;)

The results are superb accuracy. The rod is very bendy and flexible and that's totally fine. Slow down the Z motor and update the steps. According to Prusa calculator and forum the resulting steps 6400 and 3mm speed.

GCode post-mod:

  • M92 Z6400 # update steps
  • M203 Z3 # slow down Z
  • M500 # save to EEPROM

References:

  • http://www.soliforum.com/topic/2154/fixing-banding-zwobble-with-fine-threaded-zrod/
  • http://prusaprinters.org/calculator/
  • http://www.metrication.com/engineering/threads.html (M3 pitch 0.5 for Prusa calculator above)

Changelog:

2016-12-11 - My M3 nuts worked their way out so I've added another part that will hold them in place. One is to be placed above and one below the part with the hex opening. Drill holes to size.. I drilled mine slightly wider for 6-32 screws.

description.text: This is a multi-part thing. The idea is to keep the electronic dust free as much as possible, and to provide firm support to the frame. Created extensions secure the LCD from bending over, and make it easier to stand on the frame, especially when introducing files from SD.

Mounting:

First assemble the cover in the following order:

1) Put "lcd rear.stl" laying on flat surface.
2) Put the "lcd back" parts with their flat side laying on the back. You will notice there is one sharp angle of the mask. That is top left corner, when you look at the LCD from front.
3) On top of that, put the LCD. Make sure the holes of the red PCB are aligned.
4) Put the "lcd front 1". Make sure the holes and the top left corner are aligned.
5) Put the "lcd front 2". Make sure the holes and the top left corner are aligned.
6) Secure all the layers with m3 25 or 30 screws. I had 2x25 from Sun Hokey kit, so I had to use also 2x30. If all of them were 25 in length, it would be perfect. put the nuts on the back of "lcd rear" part.

7) Put the acrylic in mask inset, together with screwed on nuts, as described in the Sun Hokey kit. Let the whole assembly rest on the acrylic frame, above the "PRUSA i3" sign. The extensions should go from the front and back. Slide the assembly on the rim of the frame, and screw the nuts from the back, on the originally put m3 30.

description.text:
NOTE: I have notice a small mistake with the doors for the purple and orange rooms: the files are correct, but in my picture above I have glued the orange doors to the purple room, and vice versa.

This has been printed finally. And it has turned out well! I have not glued the entire model together, instead I have created 7 sections: the top and bottom, the four corners, and the center. These just slide together when playing. I may end up gluing the together later, but for now they remain separate.

This is version two of the original, it's a complete reproduction with a focus on assembly over painting. I have also made the model overall taller (48mm vs 35.2mm) and more detailed. (I have also removed the lego pegs).

All pieces can build on a small build platform with some exceptions. But these could be easily split and glued together. In fact, you may want to take some pieces that are the same color (the stairs for example) and print them as one piece to avoid gluing them.

The included build script creates the STL files you see attached using the attached SCAD file.

General assembly of rooms works as follows: The room plate is glued on top of the interior wall plate. This is slotted into the two exterior walls. Finally, a corner cap is glued where the exterior walls adjoin.

As for the keyholders, you need to use the two special ones for the gold room and the blue room's window. They have a cut-out in them that accomodates the nearby room's corner cap that would otherwise intersect.

Printer:

Original Prusa I3 MK2

Notes:

Corners should be printed with supports. The exterior walls are printed with their inside facing on the build plate (and their outside facing pointed up).

The keys have built in support and should be printed upside down.

In terms of kerf, it would be possible to directly add it. But currently the models do not have any because the prusa printer I am using does a great job at part accuracy. I do have to apply some sanding for the parts to fit, but it is good for the glue to sand the edges anyway. I would also say that by assembling it as seven separate sections, there are some gaps that would need to be filled if I decided to take the seven and combine them as one. I think that this could be avoided if I had taken care to assemble it as all one piece. (I could also take the hallway pieces and print them as a single piece to add accuracy).

One last caveat: The room and interior plates do not have mitering. All of them need mitering except the white room. However, instead of modifying the model I simply cut the edges with a pair of flush cutters.

Levine collaborated with MakerBot to create custom-made sunglasses for Levine's Fall/Winter 2012 collection which were presented at NY Fashion Week on February 10, 2012. version 1 has a smaller hole with almost not tolerance, but cuts closer to the edge, getting more of the crimp out.

version 2 has a larger hole and is much easier to use right off the bed. it tends to leave the lip on the crimp, similar to a roll crimp. Printing this one is preferred, but getting the slug in may be more difficult.

neither version currently has an easy way to replace the knife should it dull or break.

Notes:

Print it with the shell hole pointing up so you don't have overhang.

description.text:
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/kk3pMjBny5e

It is best to print each piece separately rather than as the group. This is still a work in progress and may need slight filing/sanding for pieces to fit together nicely.

This is a ring size 10. Designed after Rich Stadler Wraith top from billet spin tops. This Ring is mainly designed for machinists that want to try something a little harder. The material it's designed for are MokuTi ( a type of Titanium) and Stainless Steel for the spikes. One important thing to mention is this ring is to be press fit together and is at a high tolerance. Some sanding with high grit sandpaper can be used to get it to press fit, but machining to tight fit is recommended.

VERTICAL Print:

I used 50% speed for the first 0.3mm layer & 20% speed for the rest of the 0.1mm layers. Slow to 10% on the tongue. .

The tongue will not print straight. It helps to place it on a flat surface right after printing until cooled. My printer gives a body bulge but requires less work on the ends.

HORIZONTAL Print:

Printed @ 50% speed with 0.1mm layers. Reduced speed to 10% at the latch around 1.5mm. Cleaned latch with #56 index bit & knife. Used file & sandpaper for the rest of the body. Requires more work on the ends, but provides a nice finish.

GENERAL INFO:

The ends have to be formed by hand. Use the attached diagram for sizes.

The battery has to fit between the latch and tongue.

Trial fit with out the battery will indicate good fit up. It will need more battery clearance if the door will not close with battery installed.

I would print one while the original door is available so it can be used for a guide.

Requires a lot of TLC cleaning and fit up.

My personally designed PlayStation VR stand was made with sleek style and functionality in mind. Its tilted headband bracket and forehead rest is positioned at such an angle where when strapped on, the VR sits fairly level and facing straight. There are four countersunk holes in the base for small rubber pads (not necessary for use) that can be glued into them for limited sliding on smooth surfaces.
